Introduction

As a analyst for a global industrial manufacturing company. CEO has a requested on performing an analyis on workplace injury data to provide CEO the solution and answer to the journalist about workplace safety practices. The CEO questions are 1. Of the various safety regimes in place across our company, whihc one would I recommend become the international stardard for our company, based soly on injury prevention performance 2. It has been suggested by senior management that industry experience is more important than the safety regime when it comes to preventing injuries. His idea is that a policy directed at lowering employee turnover to reduce injury rates. Does available data support this assertion?

Data

Before analysing the workplace injury, we need to understand the data Data set contains counts of injuries and hours work aggregated by the experience level of the workers and the workplace safety regime in place at the factory. The data was collected for 12 months of operaton.

Variables are: - Injuries - count of injuries in group - Safety - the safety regime in place for group - Hours - total hours worked by this group - Experience - the experience level of group

I started by loading necessary library for performing this analysis. Then I read in data and explore the data. After that I clean the data, changing safety and experience into factor and injuries and hours into integer.

Model

Poisson Model

I initially choose a Poisson GLM for count data to model the numbeer of injuries, with the safety regime, level of experience, and hour worked as covariates. Stepwise selection based on the AIC was cosen to determine which variables should be used. Both backward and forward selection were used to find an optimal model based on lowest AIC.

# full model with all possible interactions for backwards selection:
full_interaction_model <- glm(data = data,
                              formula = Injuries ~ Safety * Experience * Hours,
                              family = poisson(link = "log"))

# model with no variables present for forwards selection:
null_model <- glm(data = data,
                  formula = Injuries ~ .,
                  family = poisson(link = "log"))

# perform backward and forward selection:
backward_sel_model <- stepAIC(full_interaction_model, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
forward_sel_model <- stepAIC(null_model, scope = .~.^3, direction = "forward", trace = 0)
# inspect models

Backward and forward selection arrive at the exact same model, which incluse all variables as well as interaction of safety and hours, and interaction of experience and house, and interaction of safety, experience, and hours. Then I will inspect the residual plots using the simulation method provided by the DHARMa package.

# simulate residuals from the model:
poisson_residuals = simulateResiduals(backward_sel_model)

# plot observed quantile versus expected quantile to assess distribution fit and predicted vakue versus standardised residuals for unmodelled pattern in the residuals.
plot(poisson_residuals)

There is very strong evidence to suggest that the distribution of the residuals does not match the expected distribution under the Poisson GLM. Additionally, the quantiles of the residuals (red line) show the standaradized residuals spread out as predicted value decrease in quantile1 and predicted value increase in quantile 4.

To provide a visual aid in detecting deviations from uniformity in y-direction, the plot of the residuals

disp_result <- dispersiontest(backward_sel_model)
print(disp_result)
##

## dispersion

The p-value for the test of dispersion was highly significant (z = 2.39, p = 0.008509) which indicates that the data is more variable than expected under the Poisson GLM. Therefore, I consider negative binomial model, which is more flexible and can use with dispersed count data.

Negative-Binomial model

# specify full and null models:
NB_full_model <- glm.nb(data = data, formula = Injuries ~ Safety * Experience * Hours, link = "log")
NB_null_model <- glm.nb(data = data, formula = Injuries ~ ., link = "log")

# perform backward and forward selection:
NB_backward_sel_model <- stepAIC(object = NB_full_model, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
NB_forward_sel_model <- stepAIC(NB_null_model, scope = .~.^3, direction = "forward", trace = 0)

# Inspect models:
formula(NB_forward_sel_model)
## Injuries ~ Safety + Experience + Hours + Safety:Hours + Safety:Experience
formula(NB_backward_sel_model)
## Injuries ~ Safety + Experience + Hours + Safety:Experience + 
##     Safety:Hours
AIC(NB_backward_sel_model)
## [1] 664.8223
AIC(NB_forward_sel_model)
## [1] 664.8223

Backward and forward selection arrive at the exact same model, which includes all variables as well as the interaction of safety and hours, interaction of safety and experience. I can inspect the residual plots using the simulation method provided by the DHARMa package.

# simulate residuals from the model:
NB_residuals = simulateResiduals(NB_backward_sel_model)

# plot observed quantile versus expected quantile to assess distribution fit, and lue versus standardised residuals for unmodelled pattern in the residuals
plot(NB_residuals)

The residual plots still show significant deviation in residual distribution from the expected distribution under a negative binomial GLM, however, they are smaller than for the Poisson model. Additionaly, there is no pattern in the residuals when plotted the model prediction. There are so much improvement from Poisson.

Conclusion

The coefficient estimates of the negative binomial GLM fit indicate that the number of injuries is significantly lower rate for safety regime 2 (78.31% ,p(adj.) = 0.0073, se = 0.4342, CI 0.0926: 0.5079) compared to safety regime 1. Additionally, subjects who have experience level 4 had significantly lower number of injuries compared to experience level 1 (86.99%, p (adj.) = 1.287328e-10, se = 0.2972, CI [ 0.07266859, 0.2329755]).

Overall, the Poisson GLM was a poor fit to the data, as the data was overdispersed with respoect to it. Additionally, the AIC for the best Poisson GLM was 1206.404, and the AIC for the best negative binomial GLM was 664.8223, which substantially lower and indicates the latter is a much better fit to the data.

To answer the question among the various safety regimes, the safety regime 2 is the one I recommend to become the international standard for our company. It is because safety regime 2 have lowest rate of getting injuries at 78.31% compared to safety regime 1.

For the suggestion of senior management that industry experience is more important than safety regime when it comes to preventing injuries. Persons with experience level 4 has signifcantly lower rate of injuries at 83.99% compared to experience 1.
